    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Sarcocornia meyeriana</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_9761",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Low, succulent, salt-tolerant annual bush with a short taproot and fleshy branching stems that are regularly jointed. Leaves not obvious and reduced to small fleshy lobes. Small flowers arranged in threes at joints in stem – the central flower the largest. Usually green but turns red when older or salt stressed.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9762",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Typically reach a height of 30-50 cm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9763",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to Southern Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Southern Namibia to KwaZulu-Natal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9764",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Salt-tolerant plant that occurs low on soft substrata both on the margins of marine lagoons and in estuaries, close to the high water mark<i>. </i>Also found in saline environments inland. May consist of more than one regional subspecies.</p><p>Species in this genus have a long history of use as food plants in Europe and North America. The stem segments can be eaten raw in salads, pickled, or cooked as a vegetable.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9765",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9766",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Members of this genus are typically wind pollinated and produce small seeds which are dispersed by wind or water.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9767",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>This genus contains several other local species. The Coastal samphire <i>S. littorea</i> forms similar or larger, woody bushes, but is a perennial and is found above the high water mark on rocky shores, rather than on soft substrate. Several shorter species such as the Glasswort samphire <i>S. tegetaria</i> form creeping underground runners and send up numerous short vertical stems to create a ‘lawn’ in the upper intertidal of estuaries and lagoons.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9768",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
